What was your favourite Dot Cotton moment? For me, it’s when Jim Branning proposed to her on the London Eye and her wry little smile as she looked out over the Thames. Others will pick the time she talked to her step-granddaughter Sonia over the internet and got scared by her own webcam, or the time she panicked with her Sat Nav and drove her car the wrong way down a dual carriageway. In a Walford residency that spanned three decades, there are almost too many stand-out moments to count. Dot Cotton was a lot of things to a lot of people, but however people remember her best, the one thing we can agree on is that she was an icon. So when the news broke of June Brown’s death, my heart sank. EastEnders simply wouldn’t be the same without her. Until recently, we had been fortunate to not know what that looked like – June joined the soap just a few months after it launched and only left for good in 2020. Having invested much of my adult life in the stories of various soap characters, to lose Dot felt personal. Her character seemed to exist well beyond the screen to the point where it’s her unmistakable aura I remember most, rather than any singular moment. When the character exited the soap permanently in 2020, she left behind a lasting impression of chainsmoking and an East End drawl – a loss that is felt even more keenly now that June Brown has also gone. Dot felt like more than just a soap character to me. Over her time on Albert Square, we watched her devote much of her life to her beloved launderette, which became as much the fabric of Albert Square as the Queen Vic. We watched her struggle to parent her unparentable son Nasty Nick as he relentlessly turned up to steal her money and make her life difficult. But we also watched as she forgave him and took on everyone else who needed a home too, including Fatboy, whose off-screen death in 2015 was all the more upsetting because Dot was at home waiting for him. From her hair rollers to her hypochondria, Dot was nothing short of legendary. {"@context":"https://schema.org","@type":"VideoObject","name":"Metro.co.uk","duration":"T1M2S","thumbnailUrl":"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2022/04/04/14/56203179-0-image-a-158_1649077702880.jpg","uploadDate":"2022-04-04T14:07:40+0100","description":"EastEnders star June Brown, best known for her role as chain-smoking Dot Cotton, has died at the age of 95, the BBC has announced.","contentUrl":"https://videos.metro.co.uk/video/met/2022/04/04/6008232254069455027/480x270_MP4_6008232254069455027.mp4","height":270,"width":480}  To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web
